# Angular Component File Structure

## MANDATORY: Three-File Component Structure

**NEVER** use inline `template:` or `styles:` in the `@Component` decorator.

**ALWAYS** create three separate files for each component:

### 1. `*.component.ts` — Logic & Signals

Contains:
- Component class with Angular logic
- Signal-based inputs/outputs (`input()`, `output()`)
- Computed signals (`computed()`)
- Lifecycle hooks
- Component metadata with `templateUrl` and `styleUrls`

```typescript
import { Component, ChangeDetectionStrategy, input, output, computed } from '@angular/core';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-person-card',
  standalone: true,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  imports: [CommonModule],
  templateUrl: './person-card.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./person-card.component.scss'],
  host: {
    'class': 'block',
    '[class.active]': 'isActive()',
  },
})
export class PersonCardComponent {
  // Signal inputs
  person = input.required<Person>();
  isActive = input(false);
  
  // Computed signals
  fullName = computed(() => `${this.person().firstName} ${this.person().lastName}`);
  
  // Signal outputs
  selected = output<Person>();
  
  onSelect() {
    this.selected.emit(this.person());
  }
}
```

### 2. `*.component.html` — Template with DaisyUI & Tailwind

Contains:
- HTML structure
- DaisyUI semantic classes (`btn`, `card`, `badge`, etc.)
- Tailwind utility classes (`flex`, `gap-4`, `text-lg`, etc.)
- Angular template syntax (`@if`, `@for`, signal bindings)

```html
<div class="card bg-base-100 shadow-xl">
  <div class="card-body">
    <h2 class="card-title">{{ fullName() }}</h2>
    
    @if (person().email) {
      <p class="text-sm text-base-content/70">{{ person().email }}</p>
    }
    
    <div class="card-actions justify-end">
      <button class="btn btn-primary btn-sm" (click)="onSelect()">
        Seleccionar
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

### 3. `*.component.scss` — Custom Styles Only

Contains:
- **ONLY** styles that cannot be achieved with Tailwind/DaisyUI
- Complex animations
- CSS Grid layouts requiring custom properties
- Very specific `:host` styles
- SCSS variables, mixins, or nesting (if needed)

**Keep this file minimal or empty.** Most components won't need custom styles.

```scss
/* Only if absolutely necessary */
:host {
  display: block;
}

/* Complex animation not available in Tailwind */
@keyframes pulse-custom {
  0%, 100% { opacity: 1; }
  50% { opacity: 0.5; }
}

.custom-animation {
  animation: pulse-custom 2s ease-in-out infinite;
}

/* SCSS nesting example (if needed) */
.card {
  &__header {
    // Custom styles
  }
  
  &__body {
    // Custom styles
  }
}
```

## File Organization

All three files must be in the **same directory**:

```
features/persons/components/person-card/
├── person-card.component.ts
├── person-card.component.html
└── person-card.component.scss
```

## Why Separate Files?

1. **Separation of Concerns**: Logic, structure, and style are independent
2. **Readability**: Easier to navigate and understand each aspect
3. **Tooling**: Better IDE support, syntax highlighting, and linting
4. **Collaboration**: Multiple developers can work on different aspects
5. **Maintainability**: Changes to template don't clutter TypeScript file
6. **DaisyUI/Tailwind**: Templates can be long with utility classes

## Examples

### ❌ BAD — Inline Template & Styles

```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-person-list',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="table table-zebra">
        <!-- ... long template ... -->
      </table>
    </div>
  `,
  styles: [`
    :host { display: block; }
    .custom-class { color: red; }
  `],
})
export class PersonListComponent {}
```

### ✅ GOOD — Separate Files

```typescript
// person-list.component.ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-person-list',
  standalone: true,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  imports: [CommonModule],
  templateUrl: './person-list.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./person-list.component.scss'],
})
export class PersonListComponent {
  persons = input.required<Person[]>();
  selected = output<Person>();
}
```

```html
<!-- person-list.component.html -->
<div class="overflow-x-auto">
  <table class="table table-zebra">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Nom</th>
        <th>Cognoms</th>
        <th>Email</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      @for (person of persons(); track person.id) {
        <tr (click)="selected.emit(person)">
          <td>{{ person.firstName }}</td>
          <td>{{ person.lastName }}</td>
          <td>{{ person.email }}</td>
        </tr>
      }
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>
```

```scss
/* person-list.component.scss */
/* Empty or minimal — Tailwind handles everything */
```

## Migration from Inline Templates

If you encounter inline templates, refactor immediately:

1. Create `*.component.html` file
2. Move template content from `template:` to HTML file
3. Replace `template:` with `templateUrl: './component-name.component.html'`
4. Create `*.component.scss` file (can be empty)
5. Replace `styles:` with `styleUrls: ['./component-name.component.scss']`

## Exceptions

**NONE.** This rule applies to ALL components without exception.

Even for tiny components (like a simple button wrapper), use separate files for consistency and future maintainability.
